revision.text:
'''Apographa''' refers to established copies or transcripts of certain texts, usually religious or [[ecclesiastical]], rather than the [[The Original Autographs|original autographs]] by the original authors or writers.<ref>Paolo Sacchi - [https://books.google.com/books?id=1AHUAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA91&lpg=PA91&dq=apographa+definition&source=bl&ots=yVb8ZzpmRN&sig=QQSZsT-YQvfCjc4uDkDe4jFkvMA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE0Jb93ZjUAhUM7YMKHZKiCMsQ6AEISTAH#v=onepage&q=apographa%20definition&f=false The History of the Second Temple Period] A&C Black, 2004. Chapter 2 - The Jewish Culture of the Sixth Century BCE. Page 91.</ref><ref>[https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/apograph Definition of apograph - plural apographa] Merriam-Webster.</ref><ref>[http://www.truthbpc.com/v3/main.php?&page=resources/vpp_08 Identification Of God's Preserved Words (I) - Inspiration, Preservation, and Translations: In Search of the Biblical Identity of the Bible-Presbyterian Church] - Lesson 8. B. Autographs Only or Apographs Also? truthbpc.com.</ref>
== Issues== There are scholars and theologians who consider only the original autographs of Scripture as infallible and as final authority, while others hold more to what is called the "Ecclesiastical Text" view, that [[Bible Canon|Scripture canon]] is also authoritative in various renderings in later copies or [[Bible manuscript#Textual criticism|manuscript traditions]], or established "apo-grapha" (meaning "copied-writings"), and not just the [[Biblical manuscript|original autographs]] alone. The reason being that the "original autographs" no longer actually exist, in tangible extant form, so later verified copies of copies, or "apographa", are the only real tangible or present "canon" that we have, and providentially preserved for current knowledge. And that the "apographa" or "Ecclesiastical Text" is all that is really available and should be mainly considered realistically, from established and accepted confessions, church traditions, revivals, productivity, understandings, and interpretations, and should be all that is accepted reasonably, efficiently, or sufficiently, for study or edification.<ref> Dr. Jeffrey Khoo - [http://www.deanburgonsociety.org/Preservation/sola.htm SOLA AUTOGRAPHA OR SOLA APOGRAPHA? A CASE FOR THE PRESENT PERFECTION AND AUTHORITY OF THE HOLY SCRIPTURES ] - Dean Burgon Society. Retrieved 31 May 2017.</ref><ref> A. J. MacDonald, Jr. - [https://ajmacdonaldjr.wordpress.com/2016/06/24/the-ecclesiastical-text/ The Ecclesiastical Text] - wordpress.com.</ref>
Other theologians and scholars hold to what's called the "Critical Text" position,<ref>[https://www.gotquestions.org/critical-text.html Question: "What is the Critical Text?"] - GotQuestions.org.</ref> such as put forth by [[Westcott and Hort]], that seeks to find out and put forth what the original Apostles and Prophets actually wrote, regardless of later tradition or confessional history, or "majority text" views.<ref name="gotquestions critical text">[https://www.gotquestions.org/verbal-plenary-preservation.html What is Verbal Plenary Preservation?] - GotQuestions.org.</ref> Regarding Westcott and Hort's work, according to Bible scholar and translator [[Bruce M. Metzger]], "the general validity of their critical principles and procedures is widely acknowledged by scholars today."<ref>Bruce M. Metzger, ''The Text of the New Testament: Its Transmission, Corruption, and Restoration'', p. 136.</ref><ref>Bruce M. Metzger - [https://www.christianbook.com/textual-commentary-greek-testament-second-edition/bruce-metzger/9781598561647/pd/561642?event=AFF&p=1011693&#CBD-PD-Description A Textual Commentary on the Greek New Testament, Second Edition (companion to the UBS Greek NT)]</ref>
