In [[ecology|ecological]] theory, the '''Hutchinson's ratio''' is the [[ratio]] of the size differences between similar [[species]] when they are living together as compared to when they are isolated. It is named after [[G. Evelyn Hutchinson]] who concluded that various key attributes in species varied according to the ratio of 1:1.1 to 1:1.4.<ref Name="Harvey&Silvertown ">{{cite book |title=New Scientist Sep 15, 1983; Vol. 99, No. 1375 |last= Harvey & Silvertown |first= |authorlink= |author2=Paul Harvey |author3=Jonathan Silvertown |publisher=Reed Business Information |location= |issn=0262-4079 |page=760 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jRkGXTV7z3MC&pg=PA760 }}</ref>
